06325nmm a2201069Ia 9781479886265DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814798862657 a10.18574/nyu/9781479886265.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)681047  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHN39.U6bD39 2020 7aREL0121102bisacsh04a303.3/722231 aDay, Maureen K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCatholic Activism Today :bIndividual Transformation and the Struggle for Social Justice /cMaureen K. Day. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource :b12 black and white illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReligion and Social Transformation ;v1100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1 JustFaith Ministries and the Discipleship Style: A Sociohistorical Context -- t2 The Culture of Catholic Civic Engagement: Catholicity and Core Values -- t3 From Private Belief to Public Call: Transforming American Catholics -- t4 Christ- Centered Discipleship: A Theology of Pragmatic Reverence -- t5 Transforming Community: Gathering and Sending American Catholics -- t6 The State, the Market, and Poverty: Seeking Justice -- t7 Compassion: Knowledge through Stories -- tConclusion: JustFaith Ministries and the American Catholic Landscape -- tAcknowledgments -- tAppendix A Detailed Methods -- tAppendix B Overview of JustFaith Ministries Programs -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUncovers why Catholic organizations fail to foster civic activismThe American Catholic Church boasts a long history of teaching and activism on issues of social justice. In the face of declining religious and community involvement in the twenty-first century, many modern-day Catholic groups aspire to revive the faith as well as their connections to the larger world. Yet while thousands attend weekly meetings designed to instill religiosity and a commitment to civic engagement, these programs often fail to achieve their more large-scale goals.In Catholic Activism Today, Maureen K. Day sheds light on the impediments to successfully enacting social change. She argues that popular organizations such as JustFaith Ministries have embraced an approach to civic engagement that focuses on mobilizing Catholics as individuals rather than as collectives. There is reason to think this approach is effective—these organizations experience robust participation in their programs and garner reports of having had a transformative effect on their participants’ lives. Yet, Day shows that this approach encourages participants to make personal lifestyle changes rather than contend with structural social inequalities, thus failing to make real inroads in the pursuit of social justice. Moreover, the focus on the individual serves to undermine the institutional authority of the Catholic Church itself, shifting American Catholics’ perceptions of the Church from a hierarchy that controls the laity to one that simply influences it as they pursue their individual paths.Drawing on three years of interview, survey, and participant observation data, Catholic Activism Today offers a compelling new take on contemporary dynamics of Catholic civic engagement and its potential effect on the Church at large.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aChristian sociologyxCatholic Church2DLC. 0aChristian sociologyxCatholic Church. 0aChristian sociologyzUnited States2DLC. 0aChristian sociologyzUnited States. 0aChurch and social problemsxCatholic Church2DLC. 0aChurch and social problemsxCatholic Church. 0aChurch and social problemszUnited States2D